**Collecting data**: Start by collecting a large dataset of smartphone photo gallery scenes. This can be done by searching for images on the internet and filtering them based on the desired category (nature).

**Cleaning the data**: Remove any images that do not contain any recognizable objects or details related to nature (e.g. landscapes, animals, weather, plants). This will ensure that only realistic and vivid scenes are included in the generated list.

**Preprocessing the data**: Use NLTK's Natural Language Toolkit (NLTK) library to preprocess the text data. This includes tokenizing the text into words, removing stop words (common words like "the", "and", "a"), and stemming the words to their root form.

**Creating a list of unique scenes**: Using NLTK's word frequency analysis, generate a list of unique words that appear in the preprocessed text data. This will help identify the most common phrases and vocabulary used in the generated list.

**Filtering the list**: Use NLTK's Part-of-Speech (POS) tagging to identify the nouns, adjectives, and verbs used in the preprocessed text data. This will help identify the main elements in each scene, such as animals, landscapes, weather, and plants.
